    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so how do i actually \"brace\" my core though? i hear people talking about it all the time but i dont really get how to do it during the actual pull so the weight doesnt just yank me forward",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bracing your core is like trying to hold a balloon in your stomach while you are about to be squeezed by a giant, invisible hand. You need to imagine a tight, rubbery band around your waist that is ready to snap, but you must do this *before* you even lift the bar, not during the pull. If you brace too hard, you will just be holding your breath and tugging on your own muscles, which is exactly what causes your lower back to collapse.\n\nThink of it as a \"goblin shield\" around your spine. When you feel that tightness in your lower back, it means your core is acting like a weak link, letting the weight yank you forward. You need to engage your abs and obliques so hard that your spine feels like it is being hugged by a giant, invisible wall. This creates a rigid column that transfers the force directly to your hips and glutes, rather than letting your back take the brunt of the impact.\n\nIf you are still feeling that \"yank\" during the pull, it means your core is still too loose. You need to tighten that \"goblin shield\" again before you even start the movement, and then let your hips drive the",
